we will prove theorem 10 with the aid of the following lemma: lemma 1. let a be a conservative auction with competitive ratio 1/r for n bidders.
the class of conservative auctions can be viewed as a  generalization of the class of restricted auctions and therefore our result below gives lower bounds on the performance of a broader class of auctions.
in [8], the authors define a restricted auction as one on which, for any input, the sale prices are drawn from the set of input bid values.
the random sampling profit extraction auction [5] and the core auction [7], on the other hand, use the profitextractr mechanism as a subroutine and thus  sometimes offer a sale price which is higher than the highest input bid value.
the k-vickrey auction and the random sampling optimal price auction [9] are conservative auctions.
for the three-bidder case, υ3 has competitive ratio 2.17, while the best conservative auction is no better than 2.33-competitive.
for larger numbers of bidders, however, the restriction to conservative  auctions does affect the competitive ratio.
υ2, the 1-unit vickrey auction, is conservative.
for a two-bidder auction, this restriction does not prevent  optimality.
corollary 1. the competitive ratio of any conservative  auction for an arbitrary number of bidders is at least three.
then the competitive ratio of a is at least 3n−2 n .
