we can now state our lower bound for conservative auctions.
definition 8. we say an auction bif is conservative if its  bidindependent function f satisfies f(b-i) ≤ max(b-i).
specifically, this result partially explains the form of the optimal three bidder auction.
as this 180 lower bound is stronger than the lower bound of theorem 2 for n ≥ 3, it shows that the optimal auction must occasionally charge a sales price higher than any bid in the input.
auctions in this section, we define a class of auctions that never offer a sale price which is higher than any bid in the input and prove a lower bound on the competitive ratio of these auctions.
